body:
@max-s-lab Looks good to me. If I use something like this: 
```php
$array1 = [
    'id'    => '1',
    'class' => [
        'a',
        'b',
        'c',
    ],
];
$array2 = [
    'id'    => '2',
    'class' => [
        'd',
    ],
];
$result = ArrayHelper::merge($array1, $array2);
echo "id: {$result['id']}";
echo "class-3: {$result['class'][3]}";
$result['id'] = '3';
$result['class'][] = 'e';
``` 
I get these errors in psalm with your solution: 
```shell
ERROR: MixedArrayAccess
Cannot access array value on mixed variable $result['class'] (see https://psalm.dev/051)
        echo "class-3: {$result['class'][3]}";

ERROR: MixedArrayAssignment
Cannot access array value on mixed variable $result['class'] (see https://psalm.dev/117)
        $result['class'][] = 'e';
``` 
I would also expect these errors because how should psalm know what comes out at the end if I can merge any number of arrays above with mixed structure. 
In this case I would have to assign a custom pslam type to the result or approach the problem differently.
